University catalogs at one-institution scale sit in an awkward middle ground for large language model applications. They are too large to fit in any reasonable prompt and too small to justify the operational machinery of a managed vector database. The modern default response to this regime --- chunk the documents, embed them, retrieve them at query time --- inherits well-documented failure modes around chunking boundaries, retrieval miss, and generation drift @barnett2024sevenfailures, and provides no native answer to the long-context degradation that the chunk-then-stuff pattern induces @liu2024lostinthemiddle @laban2025lostinconversation. We present the #emph[LaSalle Wiki Tutor], an AI study advisor for La Salle Campus Barcelona (Universitat Ramon Llull) that takes a different approach. The catalog is crawled once into a compiled Markdown wiki of 357 program records and 4,606 subject records mirrored across English and Spanish, each with strict YAML frontmatter. A streaming agent built on Agno and OpenAI's Responses API navigates the wiki through ten deterministic, read-only tools rather than through a vector-database substrate. Vector retrieval is preserved as a primitive, but is confined to the inside of one tool: the free-text `search_programs` tool blends BM25-F field-weighted lexical scoring @robertson2009bm25 with Model2Vec 256-dimensional static embeddings @tulkens2024model2vec at a 0.55/0.45 ratio after pool-normalisation, modulated by a small intent prior. On a 20-query benchmark that spans colloquial, bilingual, and rare-token cases, this hybrid configuration is the only mode that reaches 100% top-5 coverage; the lexical-only mode wins top-1 by a five-point margin, and the legacy token-overlap baseline reaches only 45%. The system is observable by construction: three MongoDB collections (Agno sessions, conversation metadata, and per-turn reasoning plus tool-timing traces) supply the empirical material reported here. We run the service publicly at #link("https://lasalle.generateeve.com") on a single Terraform-provisioned `t3.micro` behind a shared-token gate, with a measured median per-turn cost of #sym.dollar 0.013 and a median per-conversation cost of #sym.dollar 0.006 against a fixed monthly infrastructure cost of approximately #sym.dollar 14. The implementation is open source at #link("https://github.com/joe-carr-data/lasalle-wiki-tutor").
